It's time to tear apart our bedroom. The last room in the house where only a little decorating has been done and nothing else.
The awful electric fireplace and the hearth must go. We need to enclose the chimney, replace and smooth out the cracked plaster, and then build the closet to measure.
We always start with a rough pencil sketch...
The dirty part of the work is done.
At the back of the chimney, we found a few dead birds, very dried out :(
The translation of the given German sentence to English is:  "Everything ready for the plasterer next week."
The small side niche has turned out well.
Here comes a new closet in (but we haven't even started with the design yet 🙈)
Oh, look, what we found behind the heater!
And we even thought about installing this nice little vent flap so that the chimney doesn't get damp.
The chimney sweep has installed the cover and hood. Now it should be a little bit safer for the ravens that like to nest up there 🪺
The plasterer is finished. The floor will be laid tomorrow!
The cork underlay is in place, I have built a toilet paper roll sawdust extractor for the vacuum cleaner 😂
The floor parts are ready and can be installed. We are currently on tea break.
Buhu. Today it's progressing slowly because of incredibly complicated cuts around the door jambs, so we can have a smooth transition to the hallway (where the floor is also being replaced). @user45@twitter.com has cursed me.
Done, but at last! The crowning moment was the terrible assembly instructions for the new bed. Tonight we will sleep well!
The floor in the hallway and all the skirting boards are still missing. The decorator is coming in a month, so we currently have a bare plastered look.
Some more do-it-yourself work in the evening to cut or carve out the lower sections around the door posts, so that the floor then fits seamlessly underneath.
The cork underlay is now also in the hallway.
Yesterday we finished the floor in the hallway! Then at around 5 AM, we left to pick up Object 1 at Heathrow, then had a nap and finished up in the hallway, the beams are installed. Joints will be made once the glue is dry.
